{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cde5f0be-9a97-4286-ad8c-dc04916d09e5","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **use `System.IO.Abstractions`**:\n\n1. **Install the package:**\n   ```\n   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\n   ```\n\n2. **Inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling static methods directly:**\n   ```csharp\n   public class MyService\n   {\n       private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n       public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n       public string Load(string path) => _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n       public void Save(string path, string content) => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n       public bool Check(string dir) => _fs.Directory.Exists(dir);\n   }\n   ```\n\n3. **In production**, register `new FileSystem()` (the real implementation).\n\n4. **In tests**, use `MockFileSystem` (ships with `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`):\n   ```csharp\n   var fs = new MockFileSystem();\n   fs.AddFile(\"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{}\"));\n   var svc = new MyService(fs);\n   Assert.Equal(\"{}\", svc.Load(\"/data/config.json\"));\n   ```\n\nThis avoids hand-rolling your own `IFileWrapper` and gives you a drop-in in-memory file system for tests with no disk I/O.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75deba30-b0f8-4b27-a434-a70c81663d2e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in their .NET/C# project. They have direct calls to `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` scattered across their code, and want to know how to make them testable.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question, not a task to perform on their codebase. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":444,"requestId":"7034:358C2B:CD47A8:EE584A:69F2B602"},"id":"745d1c81-d352-461b-8715-2c17eaec48e1","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:53:15.605Z","parentId":"8fd92ebf-9835-426e-89eb-54444d52bce5"}
